It seems possible that we have an actual specimen osa lex regia preserved in a fragmentary Latin inscription, a cast of which is in the British Museum. It was discovered in 1899 on the site of the Comitium and is written in arehaic Greek letters. It perhaps gives directions as to the place and time at which certain sacrifices are to be made and indicates the penalty in case of contravention. The date of the in- scription is probably to be placed early in the 6th century B.C., and it is likely that its mutilation took place at the time os the Gallie invasion. The interpretation, however, is very uncertain.
